SIMPLE: ennoble
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ennoble
<hw>En*no"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Ennobled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Ennobling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref.
<ets>en-</ets> + <ets>noble</ets>: cf. F. <ets>ennoblir</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To make noble; to elevate in degree, qualities, or
excellence; to dignify.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Ennobling</xex> all that he
touches.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Trench.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What can <qex>ennoble</qex> sots, or slaves, or cowards?⟦br⟧
Alas! not all the blood of all the Howards.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To raise to the rank of nobility; <as>as, to
<ex>ennoble</ex> a commoner</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To raise; dignify; exalt; elevate;
aggrandize.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ennoblement</ent>⟦br⟧
